paragraphs.text: %md ##HW11.0 Broadcast versus Caching in Spark What is the difference between broadcasting and caching data in Spark? Give an example (in the context of machine learning) of each mechanism (at a highlevel). Feel free to cut and paste code examples from the lectures to support your answer. ### 11.0 Solution **Caching**: One of the most important capabilities in Spark is persisting (or caching) a dataset in memory across operations. When you persist an RDD, each node stores any partitions of it that it computes in memory and reuses them in other actions on that dataset (or datasets derived from it). This allows future actions to be much faster (often by more than 10x). Caching is a key tool for iterative algorithms and fast interactive use. You can mark an RDD to be persisted using the persist() or cache() methods on it. The first time the RDD is computed in an action, it will be kept in memory on the nodes. Spark‚Äôs cache is fault-tolerant ‚Äì if any partition of an RDD is lost, it will automatically be recomputed using the transformations that originally created it. **Broadcast**: Normally, when a function passed to a Spark operation (such as map or reduce) is executed on a remote cluster node, it works on separate copies of all the variables used in the function.Broadcast variables allow the programmer to keep a read-only variable cached on each machine rather than shipping a copy of it with tasks. Broadcast variables can be used, for example, to give every node a copy of a large input dataset in an efficient manner. **Non ML Example**: Suppose we want to join 2 files and one file is small and can be kept in memory, and the other file is 10TB in size. The join can be achieved by doing a mapside join only. In this case assume we have 4 nodes and each node can execute 2 tasks in parallel and suppose we need to run in total 16 map tasks. Without broadcast, the small file will be passed 16 times while with broadcast it will be passed only 4 times. **ML example**: Consider we want to write linear regression algorithm using gradient descent. In this scenario we will iterate over the same input training data set. As the input dataset is not changing, we would use caching here. In each iteration we are calculating the weight vector. In this case if we have multiple executors and large dataset, the task of calculating the weight vector will be distributed. As we need to pass the previous weight vector to each task, we can use broadcast to cache the weight vector, which will make sure all the executors have a copy of it versus passing the value with each task. **Code Example of caching and broadcasting:** Take the following ML code (Logistic Regression w/o regularization) as an example: - The `data` RDD is reused in each iteration, and so it is persisted across all the iterations by caching. - In each iteration, the weights `w` is broadcasted to all the nodes since all tasks need to access it. ``` def logisticRegressionGDReg(data, wInitial=None, learningRate=0.05, iterations=50): featureLen = len(data.take(1)[0].x) n = data.count() if wInitial is None: w = np.random.normal(size=featureLen) # w should be broadcasted if it is large else: w = wInitial for i in range(iterations): wBroadcast = sc.broadcast(w) gradient = data.map(lambda p: (1 / (1 + np.exp(-p.y*np.dot(wBroadcast.value, p.x)))-1) * p.y * np.array(p.x))\ .reduce(lambda a, b: a + b) w = w - learningRate * gradient / n return w data = sc.textFile('data.csv').map(readPoint).cache() logisticRegressionGD(data) ```

HW11.0 Broadcast versus Caching in Spark

What is the difference between broadcasting and caching data in Spark? Give an example (in the context of machine learning) of each mechanism (at a highlevel). Feel free to cut and paste code examples from the lectures to support your answer.

11.0 Solution

Caching: One of the most important capabilities in Spark is persisting (or caching) a dataset in memory across operations. When you persist an RDD, each node stores any partitions of it that it computes in memory and reuses them in other actions on that dataset (or datasets derived from it). This allows future actions to be much faster (often by more than 10x). Caching is a key tool for iterative algorithms and fast interactive use.

You can mark an RDD to be persisted using the persist() or cache() methods on it. The first time the RDD is computed in an action, it will be kept in memory on the nodes. Spark‚Äôs cache is fault-tolerant ‚Äì if any partition of an RDD is lost, it will automatically be recomputed using the transformations that originally created it.

Broadcast: Normally, when a function passed to a Spark operation (such as map or reduce) is executed on a remote cluster node, it works on separate copies of all the variables used in the function.Broadcast variables allow the programmer to keep a read-only variable cached on each machine rather than shipping a copy of it with tasks. Broadcast variables can be used, for example, to give every node a copy of a large input dataset in an efficient manner.

Non ML Example: Suppose we want to join 2 files and one file is small and can be kept in memory, and the other file is 10TB in size. The join can be achieved by doing a mapside join only. In this case assume we have 4 nodes and each node can execute 2 tasks in parallel and suppose we need to run in total 16 map tasks. Without broadcast, the small file will be passed 16 times while with broadcast it will be passed only 4 times.

ML example:
Consider we want to write linear regression algorithm using gradient descent. In this scenario we will iterate over the same input training data set. As the input dataset is not changing, we would use caching here.

In each iteration we are calculating the weight vector. In this case if we have multiple executors and large dataset, the task of calculating the weight vector will be distributed. As we need to pass the previous weight vector to each task, we can use broadcast to cache the weight vector, which will make sure all the executors have a copy of it versus passing the value with each task.

Code Example of caching and broadcasting:
Take the following ML code (Logistic Regression w/o regularization) as an example:

  • The data RDD is reused in each iteration, and so it is persisted across all the iterations by caching.
  • In each iteration, the weights w is broadcasted to all the nodes since all tasks need to access it. 
    def logisticRegressionGDReg(data, wInitial=None, learningRate=0.05, iterations=50):
featureLen = len(data.take(1)[0].x)
n = data.count()
if wInitial is None:
    w = np.random.normal(size=featureLen) # w should be broadcasted if it is large
else:
    w = wInitial
for i in range(iterations):
    wBroadcast = sc.broadcast(w)
    gradient = data.map(lambda p: (1 / (1 + np.exp(-p.y*np.dot(wBroadcast.value, p.x)))-1) * p.y * np.array(p.x))\
                .reduce(lambda a, b: a + b)
    w = w - learningRate * gradient / n
return w
data = sc.textFile('data.csv').map(readPoint).cache()
logisticRegressionGD(data)

%md
In the Spark-notebook-based implementation of KMeans, the centroids are sent along in every **task**.  So if the data is broken up into 100 partitions, the centroids are sent out 100 times.  Since the centroids are fixed during every iteration, it can be broadcasted to all nodes instead. Here is the plan to improve the KMeans notebook: 

1. We are reading the data from text file and caching it as we are iterating over the same data set. There is no need to modify this code.
2. centroids is defined as a global variable. Now this variable will be passed to each and every task that is run on the data file. This part is not optimized, because if we have centroids with more values or if the data file is large than we are incurring cost with the passing this read only data everytime .We can optimise this section to use broadcast variable from main function.
3. Changes to be done:
In the `nearest_centroid` calculation we will refer to the value of the broadcast centroid.
In the main function we will create an new broadcast variable based on the centroid variable.

paragraphs.text:
%md
###Answer 11.1
Loss functions consist of:
- loss term (L(mi(w)), expressed in terms of the margin of each training example
- regularization term R(w) expressed as a function of the model complexity


**Binary classification using Linear SVM v/s L2 penalized logistic regression:**

Linear SVM :
 - Loss function is 1/2 ‚ïëw‚ïë¬≤ subject to constraint y_i(w x_i + b) - 1 >= 0

Logistic Regression:
 - The loss term comes from the log likelihood function
 - The regularization term comes from the L2 norm of w
 - Loss function = sum_over_examples(1 + exp(-y_i (w'x_i + b))) + ùù∫ ‚ïëw‚ïë¬≤

Linear Support Vector machines try to maximixe the margin between the two classes while Logistic regression optimizes the log likelihood function.
Linear SVM and logistic regression are both trying to find good linear decision boundaries but in case of SVM the points near the margin matter the most while in logistic regression all the points in the training set matter as all points contribute to error made.

In both cases, the solution is a hyperplane given by w<dot>x = bias.

However the loss functions for SVM and Logistic regression are different and thus will not yield same result. Because the linear SVM takes points close to the decision boundary into more account, the decision boundary given by the SVM will be closer to the geometric mean between closest points. 

Both SVM and Logistic Regression yield predicted labels, but Logistic Regression outcomes can be interpreted as probabilities of each label. 

**Binary classification using Linear SVM v/s perceptron learning algorithm:**

Loss function for Perceptron algorithm:
 ‚àë(‚àí.x_iy_i)wx_iy_i

Linear Support Vector machines try to maximixe the margin between the two classes while perceptron algorithm tries to minimise the classification error.
Linear SVM try to find the dividing hyperplane with the maximum distance from training points, while the perceptron algorithm is satisfied by any hyperplane that separates the two classes.

The preceptron algorithm only updates the weight vector when the output class is different from its true class. 
The loss functions for perceptron and Linear SVM thus will not yield same result.

%pyspark import numpy as np # create dataset of points above y= x+5 and below y = x-5; cluster left above, right below. x = [0.1 + i*(0.1) for i in range(50) ] yvals = [x[i] + np.random.random_integers(low=5, high=10) for i in range(25)] # skew the lower data points yvals2 = [x[j] + np.random.random_integers(low=-12, high=-5) for j in range(25,50)] yvals.extend(yvals2) # add a few points along margins: x_ext1 = [2.5 + j*0.5 for j in range(5)] x_ext2 = [0.5 + j*0.5 for j in range(5)] y_ext1 = [p + 5.02 for p in x_ext1] y_ext2 = [q - 5.02 for q in x_ext2] x.extend(x_ext1) x.extend(x_ext2) yvals.extend(y_ext1) yvals.extend(y_ext2) #code for plotting import matplotlib matplotlib.use('Agg') import matplotlib.pyplot as plt import numpy as np import StringIO def showMPL(plot): img = StringIO.StringIO() plot.savefig(img, format='svg') img.seek(0) print "%html
" + img.buf + "
" plt.close()

%pyspark
# Create training set and labels from above:

trainset = zip(x, yvals)
labels = []
for e in trainset: 
    if e[1] > e[0] + 4.9:
        labels.append(1)
    else: 
        labels.append(-1)

# train SVM and LR models: 
import sklearn
from sklearn import svm
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

lin_svc = svm.LinearSVC().fit(trainset, labels)

lgr = LogisticRegression(fit_intercept=True).fit(trainset, labels)

# set up Decision boundaries (straight lines with coefficients and intercepts):
xmesh = [0.1 + i*(0.1) for i in range(50) ]
def svm_line(a0, a1, intcpt, x): 
    if a1 != 0.0: 
        return (a0*x*(-1) + intcpt)/a1
    else: return NaN
    
a0 = lin_svc.coef_[0][0]
a1 = lin_svc.coef_[0][1]
intcpt = lin_svc.intercept_[0]
y_svm = [svm_line(a0, a1, intcpt, e) for e in xmesh]
b0 = lgr.coef_[0][0]
b1 = lgr.coef_[0][1]
intb = lgr.intercept_[0]
y_lgr = [svm_line(b0, b1, intb, e) for e in xmesh]

# plot points and decision boundaries
red_ind = [i for i in range(len(labels)) if labels[i] == 1]
blue_ind = [j for j in range(len(labels)) if labels[j] == -1]
xred = [x[i] for i in red_ind]
yred = [yvals[i] for i in red_ind]
xblue = [x[i] for i in blue_ind]
yblue = [yvals[i] for i in blue_ind]
plt.figure(figsize=([20, 10]))
plt.close("all")
plt.scatter(xred, yred, color = "r", s=50)
plt.scatter(xblue, yblue, color = "b", s=50)
plt.axhline(y=0)
plt.plot(xmesh, xmesh, "--", linewidth=4, color = "black", label="Geom. Mean")
plt.plot(xmesh, y_svm, linewidth=4, color = "fuchsia", label="SVM separator")
plt.plot(xmesh, y_lgr, linewidth=4, color = "green", label="LR separator")
plt.legend(loc=3)
showMPL(plt)

paragraphs.text:
%md
##Answer 11.2
In general loss functions contain the loss term and the regularization term. Regularization term is not dependent on the data set and is a term used to penalise complexity of the model. This ensures that we don't overfit our model to the training data and the model will generalise well to any data that it has not seen before.

Three flavors of penalized loss function are:
**L1 or Lasso Regularization:** 
ùù∫ ‚ïëw‚ïë
L1 regularization helps perform feature selection. 

**L2 or Ridge Regularization:**
ùù∫ ‚ïëw‚ïë¬≤
Typically ridge or ‚Ñì2 penalties are much better for minimizing prediction error rather than ‚Ñì1 penalties. The reason for this is that when two predictors are highly correlated, ‚Ñì1 regularizer will simply pick one of the two predictors. In contrast, the ‚Ñì2 regularizer will keep both of them and jointly shrink the corresponding coefficients a little bit. Thus, while the ‚Ñì1 penalty can certainly reduce overfitting, you may also experience a loss in predictive power.


**Elastic Net Regularization:** 
When working with high dimensional datasets, there might be correlations between the variables resulting in multicollinearity.Elastic Net helps us catch these groups of related variables.Elastic net forms hybrid of the L1 and L2 penalties.
ùù∫ ‚ïëw‚ïë¬≤ + (1 - ùù∫)|w|  

Spark Mlib implementation of Logistic Regression with Stochastic Gradient Descent has only L1 and L2 penalties. It does not have Elastic Net penalty. 
Ref : http://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/api/python/pyspark.mllib.html#pyspark.mllib.classification.LogisticRegressionWithSGD
L1 usually corresponds to setting a Laplacean prior on the regression coefficients - and picking a maximum a posteriori hypothesis. L2 similarly corresponds to Gaussian prior. As one moves away from zero, the probability for such a coefficient grows progressively smaller. L1/Laplace tends to tolerate both large values as well as very small values of coefficients more than L2/Gaussian (tails).

Using MLLib train up a LASSO logistic regression model with the training dataset and evaluate with the testing set. What is a good number of iterations for training the logistic regression model? Justify with plots and words.

Derive and implement in Spark a weighted LASSO logistic regression. Implement a convergence test of your choice to check for termination within your training algorithm.
Weight the above training dataset as follows: Weight each example using the inverse vector length (Euclidean norm):
weight(X)= 1/||X||,
where ||X|| = SQRT(X.X)= SQRT(X12 + X22)
Here X is vector made up of X1 and X2.
Evaluate your homegrown weighted LASSO logistic regression on the test dataset. Report misclassification error (1 - Accuracy) and how many iterations does it took to converge.
Does Spark MLLib have a weighted LASSO logistic regression implementation? If so use it and report your findings on the weighted training set and test set.

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
from numpy.random import rand

def generateData(n):
 """ 
  generates a 2D linearly separable dataset with n samples. 
  The third element of the sample is the label
 """
 xb = (rand(n)*2-1)/2-0.5
 yb = (rand(n)*2-1)/2+0.5
 xr = (rand(n)*2-1)/2+0.5
 yr = (rand(n)*2-1)/2-0.5
 inputs = []
 for i in range(len(xb)):
  inputs.append([xb[i],yb[i],1])
  inputs.append([xr[i],yr[i],0])
 return inputs

lin_data = np.array(generateData(50)) 
lin_data2 = np.array(generateData(50))
print len(lin_data)

%pyspark
plt.clf()
plt.scatter(lin_data[:,0],lin_data[:,1],c=lin_data[:,2],alpha=0.5,cmap=plt.cm.bwr)
plt.xlim([-1,1])
plt.ylim([-1,1])
plt.grid()
plt.title('Linearly separable train data')
showMPL(plt)

result.msg: Non-linearly-separable dataset

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

#Modify this data generation code to generating non-linearly separable training and testing datasets (with approximately 10% of the data falling on the wrong side of the separating hyperplane. Plot the resulting datasets. 
from numpy.random import rand
import numpy as np

def nonLinear_generateData(n,skew):
 """ 
  generates a nonlinearly separable dataset with n samples. 
  The third element of the sample is the label
 """
 n1 = int(round(skew * n, 0))
 n2 = int(round((1-skew) * n, 0))
 
 xb = np.concatenate([((rand(n1)*2-1)/2-0.5),((rand(n2)*2-1)/2+0.5)],axis=0)
 yb = np.concatenate([((rand(n1)*2-1)/2+0.5),((rand(n2)*2-1)/2-0.5)],axis=0)
 xr = np.concatenate([((rand(n1)*2-1)/2+0.5),((rand(n2)*2-1)/2-0.5)],axis=0)
 yr = np.concatenate([((rand(n1)*2-1)/2-0.5),((rand(n2)*2-1)/2+0.5)],axis=0)
 inputs = []
 for i in range(len(xb)):
  inputs.append([xb[i],yb[i],1])
  inputs.append([xr[i],yr[i],0])
 return inputs

%pyspark
# Separate into train and test sets. 
train_data = np.array(nonLinear_generateData(50,0.9)) 
test_data = np.array(nonLinear_generateData(50,0.9))

%pyspark
##########################################
# Plot non-linearly separable training set
##########################################
plt.clf()
plt.scatter(train_data[:,0],train_data[:,1],c=train_data[:,2],alpha=0.5,cmap=plt.cm.bwr)
plt.xlim([-1,1])
plt.ylim([-1,1])
plt.grid()
plt.title('Non Linearly separable Training data')
showMPL(plt)

%pyspark

plt.ylim([-1,1])
plt.grid()
plt.title('Non Linearly separable Test data')
showMPL(plt)

%md
#####Using MLLib  train up a LASSO logistic regression model with the training dataset and evaluate with the testing set. What a good number of iterations for training the logistic regression model? Justify with plots and words.

result.msg: Using MLLib train up a LASSO logistic regression model with the training dataset and evaluate with the testing set. What a good number of iterations for training the logistic regression model? Justify with plots and words.

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

from pyspark.mllib.classification import  LogisticRegressionWithSGD
from pyspark.mllib.regression import LabeledPoint

iterations = [1, 10, 11, 12,20, 50,100, 200, 299, 300]
#iterations = [1,25]
# Load and parse the data

def labelPoint(values):
    return LabeledPoint(values[2], values[0:2])


trainData = sc.parallelize(train_data).map(labelPoint).cache()
testData =  sc.parallelize(test_data).map(labelPoint).cache()

plt.clf()
plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
w = [8,-2]
plt.xlabel("x")
plt.ylabel("y")
x = [-1, 1]
y = [-1,1]
plt.plot(x,y, linewidth=4.0,label='True Model',linestyle='--',color='red')

print "\n"
print "="*100
print "{0: <10} | {1: <20} | {2: <40} | {3}".format("Iteration","Testing Error","Model Weights","Intercept")
print "="*100

for itr in iterations:
    # Build the model
    model = LogisticRegressionWithSGD.train(trainData, iterations=itr,regType="l1",initialWeights=[0,0],regParam=0.01,intercept=True)
    
    # Evaluate the model on test data
    valuesAndPreds = testData.map(lambda p: (p.label, model.predict(p.features)))
    test_accuracy = valuesAndPreds.filter(lambda (v, p): v == p).count() / float(testData.count())
    
    print "{0: <10} | {1: <20} | {2: <40} | {3}".format(itr,1.0-test_accuracy,model.weights,model.intercept)
    
    y = [-i * model.weights[0] / model.weights[1] for i in x]
    plt.plot(x,y,label='Iteration {}'.format(itr),alpha=0.7,linewidth=0.6)

%pyspark
plt.grid()
plt.title('Logistic Regression using Spark MLib')
plt.scatter(test_data[:,0],test_data[:,1],c=test_data[:,2],alpha=0.5,cmap=plt.cm.bwr)
plt.legend( loc=0,borderaxespad=0.)
#plt.legend(loc='upper right', numpoints=1, ncol=3, fontsize=)
showMPL(plt)

%md
####Observation: Logistic Regression on nonseparable data with Spark MLlib

The regression reaches maximum possible accuracy (90%) in 11 iterations. We note that after 300 iterations, the weights stabilize to a tolerance of < 0.002. Because this is non-separable data, it is not clear how small the tolerance should be for weight convergence. With more test data, we could establish a reasonable value. For now, using about 0.002 as a tolerance gives us convergence at about 300 iterations.

%md
####Derive and implement in Spark a weighted LASSO logistic regression. Implement a convergence test of your choice to check for termination within your training algorithm.
Weight the above training dataset as follows: Weight each example using the inverse vector length (Euclidean norm): 
weight(X)= 1/||X||, 
where ||X|| = SQRT(X.X)= SQRT(X1^2 + X2^2) 
Here X is vector made up of X1 and X2. 
Evaluate your homegrown weighted LASSO logistic regression on the test dataset. Report misclassification error (1 - Accuracy) and how many iterations does it took to converge.

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

# Gradient function for loss 
# ‚àíy( 1‚àí 1/1+exp(‚àíy w'x))‚ãÖ(x/||x||)
#
#L1 Regularization = ||w||
#


def logisticRegressionGDReg(data, wInitial=None, learningRate=0.05, iterations=50, regParam=0.01, regType=None,convergenceTol=0.01,test_Data=None):
    featureLen = len(data.take(1)[0].features)+1
    n = data.count()
    if wInitial is None:
        w = np.random.normal(size=featureLen) # w should be broadcasted if it is large
    else:
        w = wInitial

    print '\n Logistic Regression Parameters:'
    print '='*100
    print '\n Learning Rate: {0}'.format(learningRate)
    print '\n Regularization Paramter: {0}'.format(regParam)
    print '\n Regularization Type : {0}'.format(regType)
    print '\n Convergence Tolerance : {0}'.format(convergenceTol)
    print '='*100
        
        
    for i in range(iterations):
        wBroadcast = sc.broadcast(w)
        gradient = data.map(lambda p: (1 / (1 + np.exp(-p.label*np.dot(wBroadcast.value, np.append(p.features,1))))-1) * p.label * np.array(np.append(p.features,1)) *np.reciprocal(np.sqrt(np.sum(np.square(p.features)))) ).reduce(lambda a, b: a + b)
        if regType == "Ridge":
            wReg = wBroadcast.value * 1
            wReg[-1] = 0 #last value of weight vector is bias term, ignored in regularization
        elif regType == "Lasso":
            wReg = wBroadcast.value * 1
            wReg[-1] = 0 #last value of weight vector is bias term, ignored in regularization
            wReg = (wReg>0).astype(int) * 2-1
        else:
            wReg = np.zeros(wBroadcast.value.shape[0])
            
        gradient = gradient + regParam * wReg  #gradient:  GD of Sqaured Error+ GD of regularized term 
        
        wDelta = learningRate * gradient/n
        
        if sum(abs(wDelta)) <= convergenceTol*sum(abs(wBroadcast.value)):
            print "\nAlgorithm converges after {0} iterations".format(i)
            break;
        
        w = wBroadcast.value - wDelta
    return w

%pyspark
np.random.seed(400)
w = logisticRegressionGDReg(trainData, iterations=2000, regParam=0.1, regType="Lasso")
print w

model_prediction = testData.map(lambda p: (p.label,1/(1+np.exp(-1.0*np.dot(w,np.append(p.features,1))))))

#predicted = model_prediction.map(lambda (v,p): (v,1.0 if p>0.5 else 0.0 ))

#model_prediction = testData.map(lambda p: (p.label,np.dot(ww,np.append(p.features,1))))

predicted = model_prediction.map(lambda (v,p): (v,1.0 if p>0.5 else 0.0 ))

#print model_prediction.first(), model_prediction.count()

%md
#### Observations 11.3 using weighted Logistic Regression Lasso Model

This model is still not separable and therefore an error rate of less than 10% would be very unlikely (we know 10% of the points are on the wrong side of any hyperplane). The model reached 11% error rate in 15 iterations, with a Logistic Regression tolerance of 0.01. Interestingly, if the tolerance is tuned down to 0.001, the model does not converge until about 270 iterations. At that point, the test error measured above was about 50 percent, an increase - overfitting.

Interestingly, if the tolerance is tuned down to 0.001, the model does not converge until about 270 iterations. At that point, the test error measured above was about 50 percent, an increase - overfitting.

%pyspark

# we are going to use the trainData and testData from 11.3 question
from pyspark.mllib.classification import SVMWithSGD

iterations = [1, 10, 20, 50,75,100,200,300]


plt.clf()
plt.figure(figsize=(10,8))
w = [8,-2]
plt.xlabel("x")
plt.ylabel("y")
x = [-1, 1]
y = [-1,1]
plt.scatter(train_data[:,0],train_data[:,1],c=train_data[:,2],alpha=0.5,cmap=plt.cm.bwr)
plt.plot(x,y, linewidth=4.0,label='True Model',linestyle='--',color='red')

print "\n"
print "="*120
print "{0: <10} | {1: <20} | {2: <40} | {3: <20} | {4}".format("Iteration","Testing Error","Model Weights","Intercept","Width of margin")
print "="*120

for itr in iterations:
    # Build the model
    model = SVMWithSGD.train(trainData, iterations=itr,intercept=True)
    
    # Evaluate the model on test data
    valuesAndPreds = testData.map(lambda p: (p.label, model.predict(p.features)))
    test_accuracy = valuesAndPreds.filter(lambda (v, p): v == p).count() / float(testData.count())
    
    width = 2/np.sqrt(np.sum(np.square(model.weights)))
        
    print "{0: <10} | {1: <20} | {2: <40} | {3: <20} | {4}".format(itr,1-test_accuracy,model.weights,model.intercept,width)
    
    y = [-i * model.weights[0] / model.weights[1] for i in x]
    plt.plot(x,y,label='Iteration {}'.format(itr),alpha=0.7,linewidth=0.6)

%pyspark
plt.grid()
plt.title('SVM using Spark MLib')
plt.legend( loc=0,borderaxespad=0.)
plt.xlim(x)
plt.ylim([-1,1])
#plt.legend(loc='upper right', numpoints=1, ncol=3, fontsize=)
showMPL(plt)

Evaluate your homegrown weighted soft linear svm classification learning algorithm on the weighted training dataset and test dataset from HW11.3.

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
def SVMRegGD(data, wInitial=None, learningRate=0.05, iterations=50, regParam=0.01, regType=None,convergenceTol=0.0095):
    featureLen = len(data.take(1)[0].features)+1
    n = data.count()
    if wInitial is None:
        w = np.random.normal(size=featureLen) # w should be broadcasted if it is large
    else:
        w = wInitial

    print '\n Parameters for SVM Classification'
    print '='*100
    print '\n Learning Rate: {0}'.format(learningRate)
    print '\n Regularization Paramter: {0}'.format(regParam)
    print '\n Regularization Type : {0}'.format(regType)
    print '\n Convergence Tolerance : {0}'.format(convergenceTol)
    print '='*100

        
    for i in range(iterations):
        wBroadcast = sc.broadcast(w)
        #determine suport vectors based on the formula
        sv = data.filter(lambda p: p.label * np.dot(wBroadcast.value,np.append(p.features,1))<1)
        
        if sv.isEmpty():
            break # algorithm has converged 
        
        #Now determine the gradient 
        gradient = -1* sv.map(lambda p: p.label * np.append(p.features,1) * np.reciprocal(np.sqrt(np.sum(np.square(p.features)))) ).reduce(lambda a,b:a+b) 
       
        if regType == "Ridge":
            wReg = wBroadcast.value*1
            wReg[-1] = 0 #last value of weight vector is bias term, ignored in regularization
       
        elif regType == "Lasso":
            wReg = wBroadcast.value * 1
            wReg[-1] = 0 #last value of weight vector is bias term, ignored in regularization
            wReg = (wReg>0).astype(int) * 2-1
       
        else:
            wReg = np.zeros(wBroadcast.value.shape[0])
            
        gradient = gradient + regParam * wReg  #gradient:  GD of Sqaured Error+ GD of regularized term 
        
        wDelta = learningRate * gradient/n
        
        if sum(abs(wDelta)) <= convergenceTol*sum(abs(wBroadcast.value)):
            print "\nAlgorithm converges after {0} iterations".format(i)
            print "\n Number of element in support vector: {0}".format(sv.count())
            break;
        w = wBroadcast.value - wDelta
    return w

%pyspark
np.random.seed(400)
w = SVMRegGD(trainData, iterations=2000, regType='Ridge')
print '\nWeights for the model:{0}'.format(w)

After some experimenting, our best error rate is 23 percent. Because this is reached in only 20-24 iterations, changing the tolerance (which affects the number of iterations) does not really help further.
